          "body": "Ahimelech's defense before Saul (22:14-15) is a masterpiece of priestly courage. He opens with a rhetorical question that should have stopped the trial: 'Who among all your servants is as faithful as David, even the king's son-in-law, who is captain over your guard, and is honored in your house?' (22:14). He is saying: the man you call a conspirator was, until recently, the most honored man in your court. He then explains that inquiring of God for David was routine priestly ministry, not unusual advocacy (22:15). He ends with a direct denial: 'your servant knows nothing at all of this whole affair' (22:15). Every logical and legal category favors acquittal. Saul's response in 22:16 ignores every word of it: 'You shall surely die, Ahimelech, you and all your father's household.' The verdict is not a legal conclusion; it is an emotional explosion. Calvin observed that 'nothing is more difficult for a tyrant than to hear the truth' — and Saul's response to Ahimelech proves the point."
