        "title": "The anointed king gathers the broken — a kingdom formed in hiddenness",
        "range": "22:1-5",
        "excerpt": "Everyone who was in distress, and everyone who was in debt, and everyone who was discontented gathered to him; and he became captain over them.",
        "body": "The opening of 1 Samuel 22 is deliberately anti-heroic. David arrives at Adullam not triumphantly but as a fugitive (the verb *malat*, 'escaped,' in 22:1 echoes his near-capture in Gath in chapter 21). His first company is his own family — his brothers and his father's household — people who, it should be noted, had been skeptical of him when Samuel anointed him (16:6-10). Desperation makes allies of those who were slow to believe.\n\nBut the more theologically significant gathering is in 22:2. The three descriptors — distressed, indebted, discontented — cover the full range of social failure in ancient Israelite society. *Matsoq* (distress) describes those squeezed to the breaking point by circumstances. *Nasah* (indebted) describes those under a creditor's legal claim — the ancient equivalent of bankruptcy. *Mar nephesh* (bitter of soul) describes those whose spirits have curdled under mistreatment. None of these people has anything to offer David. None of them is an asset. All of them are liabilities. And all of them come to him, and he receives them.\n\nThis is the pattern Peter Davids identifies in the New Testament's theology of reversal: the kingdom of God takes shape among those whom the existing order has discarded (cf. Luke 4:18; James 2:5). David at Adullam is not yet king; he is the one through whom the broken find a leader. Four hundred men — a number that will grow to six hundred by 1 Samuel 23:13 — are the seed of the kingdom that will eventually govern Israel. The Adullam community foreshadows the reconstituted Israel David will build when he sits on the throne.\n\nThe passage ends (22:5) with a prophetic directive that deserves more attention than it typically receives. Gad tells David to leave the stronghold and return to Judah. The stronghold was defensible; Judah was exposed. David's obedience — immediate, unargued — is the narrator's way of establishing that the anointed king is a man who moves when God speaks. This posture of prophetic responsiveness will be the defining difference between David and Saul in every subsequent chapter.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Malat* (22:1) — to escape, slip away, be delivered. The same root as 22:20 where Abiathar 'escaped.' The narrator bookends the chapter with deliverances. *Matsoq* — pressed tight, squeezed into distress. *Sar* (22:2) — captain, prince, leader; the same word used of military commanders in 22:7 where Saul offers Benjaminite loyalty through appointments of commanders (*sarim*). The contrast is sharp: David receives those who come to him freely; Saul purchases loyalty with titles."
