        "body": "The narrator's portrait of Saul in 22:6 is composed with deliberate symbolic detail. He is sitting — not marching, not planning, not leading. He holds his spear — the weapon he has already hurled at David (18:11; 19:10) and at his own son Jonathan (20:33); it has become less a military tool than a symbol of authority held tightly against the fear of losing it. The tamarisk tree at Gibeah creates a parody of a throne room: the king under a tree, his servants standing around him. The image is of a leader who can no longer move toward his enemy and so has frozen at his capital, waiting for information.\n\nSaul's speech to his servants (22:7-8) reveals the internal architecture of paranoid power. He makes three moves in two verses. First, he appeals to tribal loyalty — 'Hear now, O Benjamites!' — reminding his court that David is from Judah, not their tribe, and that a Judahite king would not give them fields, vineyards, or military appointments. Second, he reframes loyalty as a test that everyone has already failed: 'all of you have conspired against me.' The paranoid mind converts every relationship into evidence of betrayal; the absence of disclosure becomes proof of conspiracy. Third, he personalizes the grief in a way that exposes his real wound: 'there is none of you who is sorry for me.' Saul is not merely strategically threatened; he is emotionally abandoned, and he experiences his court's silence as rejection.\n\nDoeg's testimony (22:9-10) is factually accurate — David did come to Ahimelech, Ahimelech did give him bread, and Ahimelech did inquire of the LORD for him. The narrator of chapter 21 has already shown us this from David's perspective; Doeg's account adds nothing new except the sword of Goliath. But in Saul's court, accurate facts fed into a paranoid interpretive framework become lethal. The bread becomes conspiracy; the priestly inquiry becomes treason; the sword becomes the weapon of a planned ambush. This is what Chuck Swindoll calls 'the lens of jealousy' — a distortion so severe that reality itself becomes unrecognizable.\n\nThe interrogation of Ahimelech (22:12-13) follows the form of a legal proceeding but is entirely predetermined. Saul's question in 22:13 is an accusation dressed as an inquiry: 'Why have you and the son of Jesse conspired against me?' The conclusion precedes the examination. This is not jurisprudence; it is theater designed to create the record that will justify an already-determined verdict.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qashar* (22:8, 13) — to bind, to conspire in treason. *Galah* (22:8) — to uncover, to reveal, literally 'to uncover the ear'; used idiomatically for disclosing a secret to someone's ear. Saul uses it twice in one verse: 'discloses to me' and 'reveals to me.' The repetition reveals the obsession: he wants intelligence, not truth."
