        "body": "Ahimelech's defense in 22:14-15 is one of the most formally elegant speeches in the Saul narrative. He makes three moves, each of which should have been dispositive. The first is a rhetorical question about David's standing: David is the most faithful (*aman* — trustworthy, established, reliable) of all the king's servants, the king's own son-in-law, the captain of the bodyguard, honored in the royal house. Ahimelech is not naive about what has happened since David fled; he is pointing out that, from his perspective in Nob, nothing had changed in David's official status. He had no grounds to refuse him priestly service.\n\nThe second move is a claim about precedent (22:15): this was not the first time Ahimelech had inquired of God for David. He had done it before, routinely, because David was a senior military officer whose campaigns required divine guidance. The unprecedented thing was not the service; the unprecedented thing was Saul's reinterpretation of the service.\n\nThe third move is an explicit denial of knowledge: 'your servant knows nothing at all of this whole affair' (22:15). The Hebrew is emphatic — *lo yada avdekha bekhol zeh davar qatan o gadol* — 'your servant knew nothing of all this, neither small nor great.' Ahimelech is not admitting ignorance as a legal maneuver; he is stating the truth. He did not know David was a fugitive. He had been deceived (21:2), and he is saying so clearly.\n\nSaul's verdict in 22:16 ignores all three arguments without engaging any of them: 'You shall surely die, Ahimelech, you and all your father's household.' The doubling of the infinitive absolute in Hebrew (*mot tamut*, literally 'dying you shall die') is the grammar of absolute certainty — no appeal, no reversal, no mercy. John Calvin observed of this passage that when a ruler's mind has been captured by irrational fear, evidence becomes irrelevant: 'The madness of Saul did not suffer him to attend to what was right.' The verdict is the chapter's moral nadir.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Aman* (22:14) — to be firm, established, reliable; the root of *emet* (truth) and *amen*. Ahimelech calls David *ne'eman* — the most faithful man in the court. *Mot tamut* (22:16) — the doubled infinitive absolute: dying you shall die. The same construction appears in Genesis 2:17 ('you shall surely die') and throughout legal codes for capital offenses. Saul deploys it here for an innocent man."
